		<id>https://love2d.org/forums/viewtopic.php?p=160970#p160970</id>
		<link href="https://love2d.org/forums/viewtopic.php?p=160970#p160970"/>
		<title type="html"><![CDATA[Re: Jumper : 2D Pathfinder with Jump Point Search (v.1.8.1)]]></title>

		
		<content type="html" xml:base="https://love2d.org/forums/viewtopic.php?p=160970#p160970"><![CDATA[
<blockquote class="uncited"><div>you can see the top path sadly has a kink in it, but it's quite a lot better than what I was doing before.</div></blockquote>The kink is there, because at the corner, there is not grid points. The kink-path seems to be the shortest possible one on the grid.<br><br>There are algorithms for finding the true shortest path in a 2d area of polygons:<br>First remove the underlying grid. For the shortest path, all the "internal" grid nodes are not needed. Instead you only need all nodes at wall corners (assuming the player has a radius of zero). For round obstacles you would have to discretize them using polygons.<br>The start and end point of the path are not in this set of nodes, so add these two, too.<br><br>Next construct a graph out of these points by adding edges: For each pair of nodes, check if the two points can be connects by a straight line without hitting an obstacle (ray casting), if so, add an edge between the two nodes. This graph is called "visibility graph", I believe.<br><br>Then do path finding on this graph.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="https://love2d.org/forums/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=67839">micha</a> — Fri Jan 17, 2014 12:36 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
